# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fly-ball-pitcher
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ace-baseball] In baseball, an **ace** is a starting pitcher considered the best pitcher on a team's starting rotation.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ace-baseball] Barring injury or exceptional circumstances, a team's ace typically starts on Opening Day.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ace-baseball] In addition, aces are usually preferred to start crucial playoff games, sometimes on three days' rest.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ace-baseball] The term may be a derivation of the nickname of Asa Brainard (real first name: "Asahel"), a 19th-century star pitcher, who was sometimes referred to as "Ace".
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ace-baseball] In the early days of baseball, the term *ace* was used to refer to a run.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ace-baseball] Modern baseball analysts and fans have started using the term *ace* to refer to the elite pitchers in the game, not necessarily to the best starting pitcher on each team.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ace-baseball] For example, the April 27, 1981, *Sports Illustrated* cover was captioned "The Amazing A's and Their Five Aces" to describe the starting rotation of the 1981 Oakland Athletics, which featured Mike Norris, Rick Langford, Matt Keough, Steve McCatty, and Brian Kingman.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ball-boy] Quick retrieval of loose balls and delivery of the game balls to the servers are necessary for quick play in tennis.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ball-boy] In professional tournaments, every court will have a trained squad of ball boys/girls with positionings and movements designed for maximum efficiency, while also not interfering with active play.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ball-boy] As well as dealing with the game balls, ball boys/girls may also provide the players with other assistance, such as the delivery of towels and drinks.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ball-boy] There are various methods for selecting the ball boys and girls for a tournament.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ball-boy] In many tournaments, such as Wimbledon and the Queen's Club Championships, they are picked from or apply through schools, where they are selected by tournaments, and they have to go through a number of selections and tests.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ball-boy] In some other tournaments, such as the Nottingham Open, Australian Open and the US Open, positions are advertised and there are open try-outs.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ball-boy] Applicants are required to pass a physical ability assessment.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ball-boy] In addition to fitness and stamina, the abilities to concentrate and remain alert are essential.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ball-boy] In 2006, the IFAB Laws of the Game of association football were changed to allow multiple balls to be used under the direction of a referee.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ball-boy] Higher level organised matches now commonly use 6+ balls with ball boys scattered around the pitch to quicken the pace of play.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ball-boy] Typically positioned behind advertising boards surrounding the pitch, ball boys will try to be in possession of a spare ball at all times, so that this can be given to the players prior to the loose ball being retrieved.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ball-boy] Balls may also be stored on cones near sidelines, so that they are readily available for restarts, and to prevent ball boys from accelerating returns to home players, and delaying returns to away players.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ball-boy] Methods for selecting ball boys vary between grounds.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ball-boy] On occasion, away teams have complained about perceived favour of ball boys towards home sides.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ball-boy] In a 2013 EFL Cup match Eden Hazard, a member of the away team, which was trailing at the time, got into an altercation with an apparently time-wasting ball boy who was lying on top of the ball.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ball-boy] Hazard was subsequently sent off for violent conduct and suspended for three games.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ball-boy] Ball kids are stationed in out-of-play areas near the first and third base foul lines to retrieve out-of-play baseballs.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ball-boy] They should not be confused with bat boys and bat girls, who remain in or near a team's dugout and the home plate area, primarily to tend to a team's baseball bats.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ball-boy] As ball kids are stationed on the field, albeit in foul territory, they can occasionally interfere with play; such events are governed by Rule 6.01(d), the main point of which is that if the interference is unintentional, any live ball remains alive and in play.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ball-boy] For this reason, most teams will use experienced individuals who understand the rules, to minimize mistaken interference.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ball-boy] One of the more infamous examples was the use of a Hooters girl as a promotion.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ball-boy] The woman unfortunately snagged a ball that was fair and live in a Tampa Bay Rays game, throwing it to the fans.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ball-boy] The batter was awarded a double on the interference.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ball-boy] Since 1992, the San Francisco Giants have employed older men as "balldudes", instead of the traditional youths.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ball-boy] In 1993, Corinne Mullane became the first "balldudette", and she and her daughter Molly, who began working as a balldudette in the 2000s, have since been included in the National Baseball Hall of Fame as the first mother-daughter ball-retrieving duo in baseball.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ball-boy] Ball boys are stationed around the field just outside the boundary to retrieve any balls struck into the spectator stands or to the boundary rope.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/ball-boy] In India, disabled people are not allowed to be ball-boys anymore after a controversy occurred in 2017, after criticism of the Board of Control for Cricket in India surrounding the appearance of a polio-afflicted fan who had been serving as a ball-boy for a few years.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Founded in 1837, the newspaper was owned by Tribune Publishing until May 2021, when it was acquired by Alden Global Capital, which operates its media properties through Digital First Media.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Smith, the executive chairman of Sinclair Broadcast Group, closed a deal to buy the paper on January 15, 2024.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Under Smith's ownership, the paper has shifted to become politically conservative, and has seen large staff departures and declines in readership.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Abell became a journalist with the *Providence Patriot* and later worked with newspapers in New York City and Boston.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] The Abell family and descendants owned *The Sun* until 1910, when the local Black and Garrett families invested in the paper at the suggestion of former rival owner/publisher of *The News*, Charles H.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Grasty, and they, along with Grasty gained a controlling interest; they retained the name A.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Abell Company for the parent publishing company.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] That same year ***The Evening Sun*** was established under reporter, editor and columnist H.L.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] From 1947 to 1986, *The Sun* was the owner and founder of Maryland's first television station, WMAR-TV (channel 2), which was a longtime affiliate of CBS until 1981, when it switched to NBC.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] The station was sold off in 1986, and is now owned by the E.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Scripps Company, and has been an ABC affiliate since 1995.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Abell also owned several radio stations, but not in Baltimore itself (holding construction permits for WMAR sister AM/FM stations, but never bringing them to air).
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] The newspaper opened its first foreign bureau in London in 1924.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Between 1955 and 1961, it added four new foreign offices.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] As Cold War tensions grew, it set up shop in Bonn, West Germany, in February 1955; the bureau was later moved to Berlin.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Eleven months later, *The Sun* was one of the first U.S. newspapers to open a bureau in Moscow.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] A Rome office followed in July 1957, and a New Delhi bureau was opened four years later, in 1961 .
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] The paper was sold by Reg Murphy in 1986 to the Times-Mirror Company of the *Los Angeles Times*.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] The same week, a 115-year-old rivalry ended when the oldest newspaper in the city, the *News American*, a Hearst paper since the 1920s with roots dating back to 1773, folded.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] A decade later in 1997, *The Sun* acquired the Patuxent Publishing Company, a local suburban newspaper publisher that had a stable of 15 weekly papers and a few magazines in several communities and counties.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] In the 1990s and 2000s, *The Sun* began cutting back its foreign coverage.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] In 1995 and 1996, the paper closed its Tokyo, Mexico City and Berlin bureaus.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Two more—Beijing and London—fell victim to cost-cutting in 2005.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] The final three foreign bureaus—Moscow, Jerusalem, and Johannesburg, South Africa—fell a couple of years later.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] All were closed by 2008, as the Tribune Co. streamlined and downsized the newspaper chain's foreign reporting.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Some material from *The Sun*'s foreign correspondents is archived at the University of Maryland, Baltimore County.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] In 2000, the Times-Mirror company was purchased by the Tribune Company of Chicago.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] In 2014, it transferred its newspapers, including *The Sun*, to Tribune Publishing.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] The *Sun* introduced a new layout design in September 2005, and again in August 2008.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] By 2010 daily circulation as of 2010 had fallen to 195,561 and 343,552 for the Sunday edition.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] On April 29, 2009, the Tribune Company announced the lay off of 61 of the 205 staff members in the *Sun* newsroom.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] On September 23, 2011, it was reported that the *Baltimore Sun* would be moving its web edition behind a paywall starting October 10, 2011.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] On February 20, 2014, The Baltimore Sun Media Group announced that they would buy the alternative weekly *City Paper*.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] In April, the Sun acquired the Maryland publications of Landmark Media Enterprises.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] In February 2021, as part of the planned merger between Tribune Publishing and Alden Global Capital, Tribune announced that Alden had reached a non-binding agreement to sell The Sun to the Sunlight For All Institute, a nonprofit backed by businessman and philanthropist Stewart W.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] The deal was contingent on approval by Tribune shareholders of the merger deal.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] It fell apart in talks over operating agreements with Tribune for functions including human resources and customer service.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Bainum then led a failed bid to acquire all of Tribune Publishing.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Bainum subsequently founded *The Baltimore Banner*, pledging $50 million to the nonprofit outlet.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Smith, executive chairman of Sinclair Broadcast Group, reached an agreement to acquire the paper, with conservative commentator Armstrong Williams holding an undisclosed stake.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Though the transaction was independent of Sinclair, Smith said he foresaw partnerships between the paper and Sinclair properties like its flagship station, Fox affiliate WBFF-TV (channel 45).
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Smith said he believed he could grow subscriptions and advertising through a greater focus on community news and integrating technology in ways other print media publishers are not doing.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] In his first visit to the newsroom, he sparred with reporters and said the paper should emulate WBFF's news philosophy, including through non-scientific reader polls and aggressive coverage of Baltimore City Public Schools.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] He dismissed newsroom concerns about the future of public service journalism.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] In December 2024, Smith told *Sun* photographer Amy Davis that he had begun reading *The Baltimore Sun*.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Since Smith's acquisition of *The Baltimore Sun*, the paper has become more conservative, and has published more stories on Baltimore mayor Brandon Scott and his administration, as well as crime in Baltimore.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] The paper has also republished content from WBFF, also owned by Smith, the conservative news wire The Center Square, columns written by Smith's daughter, and features on new restaurants opened by Atlas Restaurant Group, which is owned by Smith's nephew.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] According to industry figures and reporting by *The Baltimore Banner*, readership of the newspaper fell by nearly half in the first year of Smith's acquisition and the *Baltimore Sun*'s website had fewer unique visitors to its website than in the year before.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] At least 20 journalists left the company, with many citing concerns they held over the way stories about juvenile crime and city government in Baltimore were written, and other reporters leaving to work for *The Baltimore Banner*.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Williams said the paper's editorial page would cease endorsing political candidates and start including more conservative viewpoints, but not at the expense of liberal ones.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] He said at the time that the newspaper may run his syndicated column "on its merits." The paper's opinion page now regularly publishes Wiliiams' columns and video commentaries.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] In June 2024, longtime managing editor Sam Davis announced he would retire at the end of the month.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Opinion editor Tricia Bishop, who has worked for the newspaper since 1999, would succeed him, with Davis staying on for a few months as a consultant for *The Baltimore Sun*'s owners.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] The Sun's primary obituary writer, Frederick N.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Rasmussen, who worked at the paper for 51 years and wrote thousands of obituaries, resigned in January 2025 over the direction of management.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] On June 10, 2024, the Baltimore Sun Guild raised concern with what it said were ethical breaches committed by management since the takeover, including the use of Fox 45's content and Williams columns that did not meet *Sun* editorial standards.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] This included language used to describe immigrants and transgender people.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] The guild demanded the *Sun* stop republishing WBFF-TV content and asked management to meet with staff to discuss their concerns.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Williams said in a statement he respected the guild's opinion but hoped the union "reciprocally appreciates legitimate managerial prerogatives in the journalistic enterprise".
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] In a subsequent *Sun* column, Williams wrote the guild and the Associated Press had no inherent authority to prescribe the way in which language is used.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Despite this, the wording used to describe immigrants in one republished Fox 45 story was eventually changed.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] The Baltimore Sun Guild has also raised concerns with the new ownership's efforts to stall contract negotiations with the paper's unionized reporters, with some employees handing out fliers at restaurants owned by David Smith's nephew, Alex, calling Smith a "union buster".
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Smith also dismissed Davis's concerns that management was proposing union-busting clauses in negotiations, including the ability to terminate employees without just cause, saying, "Nobody does that.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] There are laws to protect people from that".
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Since proposing the gag rule, management has refused to continue bargaining with the Baltimore Sun Guild, calling their latest contract their "last, best, and final offer".
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Following the *Sun*'s acquisition, one of its arts reporters asked Smith if she should look for a new job amid his acquisition.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Smith avoided the reporter's question and instead discussed his past as a "world-class furniture builder" and a photographer.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] In October 2024, the newspaper eliminated its features desk and reassigned its three reporters to news departments.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] The guild said in a statement that it would be the first time since 1888 that the paper would be without coverage of the city's cultural life.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] In February 2026, the guild criticized the paper's management for publishing AI-generated news stories providing analyses of Maryland governor Wes Moore's State of the State Address and President Donald Trump's social media posts, branding the stories as "AI slop".
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] *Politico* reported that current and former staff told *Semafor* that the paper's new mandate was "to expose fraud and misdeeds among Democratic politicians in the state" and that "David Smith, the Trump ally and longtime Sinclair steward, has been deeply involved in the team’s coverage".
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] In an interview later that month, Moore called the *Sun*'s investigation into his military career "not legitimate" and criticized Smith and other "MAGA billionaires" for using local press like their personal Twitter accounts.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Moore also said that Smith should "really be careful about throwing stones", adding that Smith had a pretty sketchy history himself.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] From 1910 to 1995 there were two distinct newspapers, *The Sun*, which was published in the morning, and *The Evening Sun*, which was published in the afternoon.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Each newspaper maintained separate reporting and editorial staff.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] After a period of roughly a year during which the paper's owners sometimes printed a two-section product, *The Baltimore Sun* now has three sections every weekday: News, Sports and alternating various business and features sections.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] On some days, comics and such features as the horoscope and TV listings are printed in the back of the Sports section.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] After dropping the standalone business section in 2009, *The Sun* brought back a business section on Tuesdays and Sundays in 2010, with business pages occupying part of the news section on other days.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Features sections debuting in 2010 included a Saturday "Home" section, a Thursday "Style" section and a Monday section called "Sunrise." The sports article written by Peter Schmuck is published only on weekdays.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] The *Sunday Sun* for many years was noted for a locally produced rotogravure Maryland pictorial magazine section, featuring works by such acclaimed photographers as A.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] The *Sunday Sun* dropped the Sunday *Sun Magazine* in 1996 and now only carries *Parade* magazine weekly.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] A quarterly version of the *Sun Magazine* was resurrected in September 2010, with stories that included a comparison of young local doctors, an interview with actress Julie Bowen and a feature on the homes of a former Baltimore anchorwoman.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Newsroom managers plan to add online content on a more frequent basis.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] The company introduced its website in September 1996.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] A redesign of the site was unveiled in June 2009, capping a six-month period of record online traffic.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Each month from January through June, an average of 3.5 million unique visitors combined to view 36.6 million web pages.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] *Sun* reporters and editors produce more than three dozen blogs on such subjects as technology, weather, education, politics, Baltimore crime, real estate, gardening, pets and parenting.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Among the most popular are Dining@Large, which covers local restaurants; The Schmuck Stops Here, a Baltimore-centric sports blog written by Peter Schmuck; Z on TV, by media critic David Zurawik; and Midnight Sun, a nightlife blog.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] A *Baltimore Sun* iPhone app was released on September 14, 2010.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] In 2008, the Baltimore Sun Media Group launched the daily paper *b* to target younger and more casual readers, ages 18 to 35.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] It was in tabloid format, with large graphics, creative design, and humor in focusing on entertainment, news, and sports.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] The paper transitioned from daily to weekly publication in 2011.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] The first issue of *The Sun*, a four-page tabloid, was printed at 21 Light Street in downtown Baltimore in the mid-1830s.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] In 1851, the newspaper moved to a five-story structure at the corner of Baltimore and South streets.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] In 1904, in the Great Baltimore Fire, the structure, known as the "Iron Building", was destroyed.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] In 1885, *The Sun* constructed a building for its Washington, D.C. bureau at 1317 F Street, NW, in Washington, D.C.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] The building is on the National Register.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] In 1906, operations were moved to Charles and Baltimore streets, where *The Sun* was written, published, and distributed for nearly 50 years.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] In 1950, operations were moved to a larger, modern plant at Calvert and Centre streets.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] In 1979, ground was broken for a new addition to the Calvert Street plant to house modern pressroom facilities.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] This facility commenced operations in 1981.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] In April 1988, at a cost of $180 million, the company purchased 60 acres (24 ha) of land at Port Covington and built "Sun Park".
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] The new building housed a satellite printing and packaging facility, and also is the newspaper's headquarters for its distribution operations.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] *The Sun*'s printing facility at Sun Park had highly sophisticated computerized presses and automated insertion equipment in the packaging area.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] To keep pace with the speed of the presses and automated guided vehicles, intelligent electronic forklifts delivered the newsprint to the presses.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] On January 30, 2022, *The Baltimore Sun* newspaper was printed for the last time at its Sun Park facility.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] It was reported that *The Sun's* printing operations would be moved to a printing facility in Wilmington, Delaware.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] In December 2022, the *Sun* announced an agreement to move its offices to 200 St.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Paul Place in downtown Baltimore, abandoning Sun Park altogether.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] After *The Sun*'s purchase in 2024, its new owners signaled plans to move the newsroom to the Bagby Building at 509 S.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Exeter St. in Little Italy, farther away from city offices and courts.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Business and advertising staffers would move to the new office over the next year.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Like many of the institutions featured in *The Wire*, the *Sun* is portrayed as having many deeply dysfunctional qualities while also having very dedicated people on its staff.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] The season focuses on the role of the media in affecting political decisions in City Hall and the priorities of the Baltimore Police Department.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Additionally, the show explores the business pressures of modern media through layoffs and buyouts occurring at the *Sun*, on the orders of the Tribune Company, the *Sun*'s corporate owner.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] One storyline involves a troubled *Sun* reporter named Scott Templeton, and his escalating tendency to sensationalize and falsify stories.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] *The Wire* portrays the managing editors of the *Sun* as turning a blind eye to the protests of a concerned line editor, in the managing editors' zeal to win a Pulitzer Prize.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] The show suggests that the motivation for this institutional dysfunction is the business pressures of modern media, and working for a flagship newspaper in a major media market like *The New York Times* or *The Washington Post* is seen as the only way to avoid the cutbacks occurring at the *Sun*.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] The finale episode, "-30-", features a montage at the end portraying the ultimate fate of the major characters.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] It shows Templeton at Columbia University with the senior editors of the fictional *Sun*, accepting the Pulitzer Prize, with no mention being made as to the aftermath of Templeton's career.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Alma Gutierrez is shown being exiled to the Carroll County bureau past the suburbs.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] In September 2008, *The Baltimore Sun* became the newspaper partner of station WJZ-TV, owned and operated by CBS; the partnership involves sharing content and story leads, and teaming up on stories.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] WJZ promoted *Baltimore Sun* stories in its news broadcasts.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] *The Sun* promoted WJZ's stories and weather team on its pages.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Since the 2024 purchase led by Sinclair chairman David Smith, the paper has partnered with Sinclair flagship WBFF-TV.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] Their respective websites republish each other's stories and articles from WBFF-TV and other Sinclair outlets appear in the paper.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baltimore-sun] This was a sticking point with the newspaper's union, since the articles sometimes did not meet The Sun's journalistic standards.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] In baseball, **base running** is the act of running from base to base, performed by members of the team at bat.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] Base running is a tactical part of the game with the goal of eventually reaching home base (home plate) to score a run.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] Batters strive to become base runners, and to enable existing base runners to move to a subsequent base or to score.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] In statistics, the number of baserunners (for example those allowed by a pitcher) is denoted by the abbreviation **BR**.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] The Official Baseball Rules uses the term **batter-runner** to identify the batter from the time he becomes a base runner until the end of the same play, whether he is successful at legally attaining first base or any subsequent base.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] The term is not applied if the batter is awarded first base (the last three items in the above list).
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] If a base runner's teammate is put out for the third out of the inning, the base runner is said to be left on base (LOB).
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] A runner who is touching a base which he is entitled to occupy may not be tagged out.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] Runners may attempt to advance from base to base on any fair ball that touches the ground.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] When a ball is hit in the air (i.e., a *fly ball*) and caught by the defending team, runners must return and touch the base they occupy—called *tagging up*—after the ball is first touched by a fielder.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] Once they do this, they may attempt to advance at their own risk.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] On a ball that touches the ground in fair territory, if there is a force, runners are required to run.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] Base runners may attempt to advance at any time while the ball is alive, even before or while the pitcher is throwing a pitch.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] The catcher—or pitcher, in lieu of delivering the pitch—often tries to prevent this by throwing the ball to one of the infielders in order to tag the runner.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] This *pick-off attempt* is usually unsuccessful in tagging out the runner but is effective in keeping the runner closer to the base.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] If the runner is tagged out while diving back to the base, it is called a *pickoff*.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] If the runner attempts to advance to the next base but is tagged out before reaching it safely, he is *caught stealing*.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] A successful attempt by the runner is called a *stolen base*.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] If a pitch gets away from the catcher, runners may also try to advance.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] This may be a *wild pitch*, if the pitcher is held responsible for the ball getting away, or a *passed ball* if the catcher is deemed to be at fault.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] Sometimes the defending team will ignore a runner who is trying to steal a base; in this case a runner is not credited with a steal, and the base is attributed to *defensive indifference*.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] An infielder who cleanly fields a ball hit on the ground, then throws it quickly and accurately, will usually get the ball to a base before the runner runs the 90 feet (27 m).
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] However, any hesitation or mistake on the part of the fielder may allow the runner to reach the base safely.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] Teams scout the opposition and take advantage of players who are poor at defense.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] For example, on a deep fly ball to center field with a man on second base, if the center fielder has a weak arm, the runner on second base may tag the base and attempt to reach third despite the risks of being tagged out.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] Base running and hitting are coordinated to produce better results in the squeeze play and the hit and run play.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] When the count is full and there are two outs, any runners forced to advance begin running as soon as the pitcher's motion obliges him to complete his pitch, as their distance from the base will not be the cause of any third out.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] Good runners also try to get extra bases when a play is being made at a different base.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] For example, a batter who hits a single should determine whether the defense's focus on another runner gives the batter a chance to reach second base.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] Sliding into a base is an important part of base running.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] The pop-up slide both ensures that the runner touches the base and elevates him to an upright posture to help him take additional bases if the defense misperforms.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] A take-out slide tries to use a collision with a fielder to keep him from taking additional action, such as throwing to achieve a double play.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] However, this move, when made independently of the attempt to reach the base, has been illegal since 2016 because of the potential for injury.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] The base coach at third base, and any batter still at home plate, may watch the ball approaching the base and may signal the base runner on the optimum slide to avoid being tagged out.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] The most baserunners allowed by a pitcher in a game since 1901 is 39, by Eddie Rommel, who pitched 17 innings in relief for the Philadelphia Athletics to defeat the Cleveland Indians, 18–17, on July 10, 1932.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] The record number of baserunners in a season is 820, by John Coleman of the Philadelphia Quakers in 1883.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/base-running] Wilbur Wood of the 1973 Chicago White Sox was the last pitcher to allow more than 500 baserunners in a season.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The initial objective of the batting team is to have a player reach first base safely; this occurs either when the batter hits the ball and reaches first base before an opponent retrieves the ball and touches the base, or when the pitcher persists in throwing the ball out of the batter's reach.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Players on the batting team who reach first base without being called "out" can attempt to advance to subsequent bases as a runner, either immediately or during teammates' turns batting.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The fielding team tries to prevent runs by using the ball to get batters or runners "out", which forces them out of the field of play.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The pitcher can get the batter out by throwing three pitches which result in strikes, while fielders can get the batter out by catching a batted ball before it touches the ground, and can get a runner out by tagging them with the ball while the runner is not touching a base.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The opposing teams switch back and forth between batting and fielding; the batting team's turn to bat is over once the fielding team records three outs.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] One turn batting for each team constitutes an inning.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] A game is usually composed of nine innings, and the team with the greater number of runs at the end of the game wins.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Most games end after the ninth inning, but if scores are tied at that point, extra innings are usually played.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Baseball has no game clock, though some competitions feature pace-of-play regulations such as a pitch clock to shorten game time.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Baseball evolved from older bat-and-ball games already being played in England by the mid-18th century.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] This game was brought by immigrants to North America, where the modern version developed.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In addition to North America, baseball spread throughout the rest of the Americas and the Asia–Pacific in the 19th and 20th centuries, and is now considered the most popular sport in parts of Central and South America, the Caribbean, and East Asia, particularly in Japan, South Korea, and Taiwan.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In Major League Baseball (MLB), the highest level of professional baseball in the United States and Canada, teams are divided into the National League (NL) and American League (AL), each with three divisions: East, West, and Central.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The MLB champion is determined by playoffs that culminate in the World Series.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The top level of play is similarly split in Japan between the Central and Pacific Leagues and in Cuba between the West League and East League.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The World Baseball Classic, organized by the World Baseball Softball Confederation, is the major international competition of the sport and attracts the top national teams from around the world.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Baseball was played at the Olympic Games from 1992 to 2008, and was reinstated on a one-off basis in 2020.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] A baseball game is played between two teams, each composed of nine players, that take turns playing offense (batting and baserunning) and defense (pitching and fielding).
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] A pair of turns, one at bat and one in the field, by each team constitutes an inning.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] A game consists of nine innings (seven innings at the high school level and in doubleheaders in college and Minor League Baseball; and six innings at the Little League level).
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] One team—customarily the visiting team—bats in the top, or first half, of every inning.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The other team—customarily the home team—bats in the bottom, or second half, of every inning.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The goal of the game is to score more points (runs) than the other team.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The players on the team at bat attempt to score runs by touching all four bases, in order, set at the corners of the square-shaped baseball diamond.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] A player bats at home plate and must attempt to safely reach a base before proceeding, counterclockwise, from first base, to second base, third base, and back home to score a run.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The team in the field attempts to prevent runs from scoring by recording outs, which remove opposing players from offensive action until their next turn at bat comes up again.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] When three outs are recorded, the teams switch roles for the next half-inning.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] If the score of the game is tied after nine innings, extra innings are played to resolve the contest.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Many amateur games, particularly unorganized ones, involve different numbers of players and innings.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The game is played on a field whose primary boundaries, the foul lines, extend forward from home plate at 45-degree angles.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The 90-degree area within the foul lines is referred to as fair territory; the 270-degree area outside them is foul territory.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The part of the field enclosed by the bases and several yards beyond them is the infield; the area farther beyond the infield is the outfield.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In the middle of the infield is a raised pitcher's mound, with a rectangular rubber plate (the rubber) at its center.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The outer boundary of the outfield is typically demarcated by a raised fence, which may be of any material and height.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The fair territory between home plate and the outfield boundary is baseball's field of play, though significant events can take place in foul territory, as well.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Protective helmets are also standard equipment for all batters.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] At the beginning of each half-inning, the nine players of the fielding team arrange themselves around the field.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] One of them, the pitcher, stands on the pitcher's mound.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The pitcher begins the pitching delivery with one foot on the rubber, pushing off it to gain velocity when throwing toward home plate.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Another fielding team player, the catcher, squats on the far side of home plate, facing the pitcher.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The rest of the fielding team faces home plate, typically arranged as four infielders—who set up along or within a few yards outside the imaginary lines (basepaths) between first, second, and third base—and three outfielders.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In the standard arrangement, there is a first baseman positioned several steps to the left of first base, a second baseman to the right of second base, a shortstop to the left of second base, and a third baseman to the right of third base.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The basic outfield positions are left fielder, center fielder, and right fielder.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] With the exception of the catcher, all fielders are required to be in fair territory when the pitch is delivered.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] A neutral umpire sets up behind the catcher.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Other umpires will be distributed around the field as well.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Play starts with a member of the batting team, the batter, standing in either of the two batter's boxes next to home plate, holding a bat.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The batter waits for the pitcher to throw a pitch (the ball) toward home plate, and attempts to hit the ball with the bat.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The catcher catches pitches that the batter does not hit—as a result of either electing not to swing or failing to connect—and returns them to the pitcher.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] A batter who hits the ball into the field of play must drop the bat and begin running toward first base, at which point the player is referred to as a *runner* (or, until the play is over, a *batter-runner*).
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] A batter-runner who reaches first base without being put out is said to be *safe* and is on base.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] A batter-runner may choose to remain at first base or attempt to advance to second base or even beyond—however far the player believes can be reached safely.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] A player who reaches base despite proper play by the fielders has recorded a hit.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] A player who reaches first base safely on a hit is credited with a single.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] If a player makes it to second base safely as a direct result of a hit, it is a double; third base, a triple.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] If the ball is hit in the air within the foul lines over the entire outfield (and outfield fence, if there is one), or if the batter-runner otherwise safely circles all the bases, it is a home run: the batter and any runners on base may all freely circle the bases, each scoring a run.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] This is the most desirable result for the batter.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The ultimate and most desirable result possible for a batter would be to hit a home run while all three bases are occupied or "loaded", thus scoring four runs on a single hit.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] A player who reaches base due to a fielding mistake is not credited with a hit—instead, the responsible fielder is charged with an error.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Any runners already on base may attempt to advance on batted balls that land, or contact the ground, in fair territory, before or after the ball lands.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] A runner on first base *must* attempt to advance if a ball lands in play, as only one runner may occupy a base at any given time; the same applies for other runners if they are on a base that a teammate is forced to advance to.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] If a ball hit into play rolls foul before passing through the infield, it becomes dead and any runners must return to the base they occupied when the play began.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] If the ball is hit in the air and caught before it lands, the batter has flied out and any runners on base may attempt to advance only if they tag up (contact the base they occupied when the play began, as or after the ball is caught).
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Runners may also attempt to advance to the next base while the pitcher is in the process of delivering the ball to home plate; a successful effort is a stolen base.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] A pitch that is not hit into the field of play is called either a strike or a ball.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] A batter against whom three strikes are recorded strikes out.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] A batter against whom four balls are recorded is awarded a base on balls or walk, a free advance to first base.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] While the team at bat is trying to score runs, the team in the field is attempting to record outs.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In addition to the strikeout and flyout, common ways a member of the batting team may be put out include the ground out, force out, and tag out.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] These occur either when a runner is forced to advance to a base, and a fielder with possession of the ball reaches that base before the runner does, or the runner is touched by the ball, held in a fielder's hand, while not on a base.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] (The batter-runner is always forced to advance to first base, and any other runners must advance to the next base if a teammate is forced to advance to their base.) It is possible to record two outs in the course of the same play.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Three outs in one play, a triple play, is possible, though rare.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Players put out or retired must leave the field, returning to their team's dugout or bench.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] A runner may be stranded on base when a third out is recorded against another player on the team.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Stranded runners do not benefit the team in its next turn at bat as every half-inning begins with the bases empty.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] An individual player's turn batting or plate appearance is complete when the player reaches base, hits a home run, makes an out, or hits a ball that results in the team's third out, even if it is recorded against a teammate.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] On rare occasions, a batter may be at the plate when, without the batter's hitting the ball, a third out is recorded against a teammate—for instance, a runner getting caught stealing (tagged out attempting to steal a base).
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] A batter with this sort of incomplete plate appearance starts off the team's next turn batting; any balls or strikes recorded against the batter the previous inning are erased.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] A runner may circle the bases only once per plate appearance and thus can score at most a single run per batting turn.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Once a player has completed a plate appearance, that player may not bat again until the eight other members of the player's team have all taken their turn at bat in the batting order.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The batting order is set before the game begins, and may not be altered except for substitutions.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Once a player has been removed for a substitute, that player may not reenter the game.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Children's games often have more lenient rules, such as Little League rules, which allow players to be substituted back into the same game.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] If the designated hitter (DH) rule is in effect, each team has a tenth player whose sole responsibility is to bat (and run).
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The DH takes the place of another player—almost invariably the pitcher—in the batting order, but does not field.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Thus, even with the DH, each team still has a batting order of nine players and a fielding arrangement of nine players.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The number of players on a baseball roster, or *squad*, varies by league and by the level of organized play.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] A Major League Baseball (MLB) team has a roster of 26 players with specific roles.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Most baseball leagues worldwide have the DH rule, including MLB, Japan's Pacific League, and Caribbean professional leagues, along with major American amateur organizations.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The Central League in Japan does not have the rule and high-level minor league clubs connected to National League teams are not required to field a DH.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In leagues that apply the designated hitter rule, a typical team has nine offensive regulars (including the DH), five starting pitchers, seven or eight relievers, a backup catcher, and two or three other reserve players.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The manager, or head coach, oversees the team's major strategic decisions, such as establishing the starting rotation, setting the lineup, or batting order, before each game, and making substitutions during games—in particular, bringing in relief pitchers.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Managers are typically assisted by two or more coaches; they may have specialized responsibilities, such as working with players on hitting, fielding, pitching, or strength and conditioning.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] At most levels of organized play, two coaches are stationed on the field when the team is at bat: the first base coach and third base coach, who occupy designated coaches' boxes, just outside the foul lines.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] These coaches assist in the direction of baserunners, when the ball is in play, and relay tactical signals from the manager to batters and runners, during pauses in play.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In contrast to many other team sports, baseball managers and coaches generally wear their team's uniforms; coaches must be in uniform to be allowed on the field to confer with players during a game.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Any baseball game involves one or more umpires, who make rulings on the outcome of each play.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] At a minimum, one umpire will stand behind the catcher, to have a good view of the strike zone, and call balls and strikes.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Additional umpires may be stationed near the other bases, thus making it easier to judge plays such as attempted force outs and tag outs.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In MLB, four umpires are used for each game, one near each base.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In the playoffs, six umpires are used: one at each base and two in the outfield along the foul lines.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Many of the pre-game and in-game strategic decisions in baseball revolve around a fundamental fact: in general, right-handed batters tend to be more successful against left-handed pitchers and, to an even greater degree, left-handed batters tend to be more successful against right-handed pitchers.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] A manager with several left-handed batters in the regular lineup, who knows the team will be facing a left-handed starting pitcher, may respond by starting one or more of the right-handed backups on the team's roster.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] During the late innings of a game, as relief pitchers and pinch hitters are brought in, the opposing managers will often go back and forth trying to create favorable matchups with their substitutions.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The manager of the fielding team trying to arrange same-handed pitcher-batter matchups and the manager of the batting team trying to arrange opposite-handed matchups.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] With a team that has the lead in the late innings, a manager may remove a starting position player—especially one whose turn at bat is not likely to come up again—for a more skillful fielder (known as a defensive substitution).
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The tactical decision that precedes almost every play in a baseball game involves pitch selection.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] By gripping and then releasing the baseball in a certain manner, and by throwing it at a certain speed, pitchers can cause the baseball to break to either side, or downward, as it approaches the batter, thus creating differing pitches that can be selected.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Among the resulting wide variety of pitches that may be thrown, the four basic types are the fastball, the changeup (or off-speed pitch), and two breaking balls—the curveball and the slider.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Pitchers have different repertoires of pitches they are skillful at throwing.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Conventionally, before each pitch, the catcher signals the pitcher what type of pitch to throw, as well as its general vertical or horizontal location.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] If there is disagreement on the selection, the pitcher may shake off the sign and the catcher will call for a different pitch.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] With a runner on base and taking a lead, the pitcher may attempt a pickoff, a quick throw to a fielder covering the base to keep the runner's lead in check or, optimally, effect a tag out.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Pickoff attempts, however, are subject to rules that severely restrict the pitcher's movements before and during the pickoff attempt.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Violation of any one of these rules could result in the umpire calling a balk against the pitcher, which permits any runners on base to advance one base with impunity.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] If an attempted stolen base is anticipated, the catcher may call for a pitchout, a ball thrown deliberately off the plate, allowing the catcher to catch it while standing and throw quickly to a base.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Facing a batter with a strong tendency to hit to one side of the field, the fielding team may employ a shift, with most or all of the fielders moving to the left or right of their usual positions.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] With a runner on third base, the infielders may play in, moving closer to home plate to improve the odds of throwing out the runner on a ground ball, though a sharply hit grounder is more likely to carry through a drawn-in infield.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Several basic offensive tactics come into play with a runner on first base, including the fundamental choice of whether to attempt a steal of second base.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The hit and run is sometimes employed, with a skillful contact hitter, the runner takes off with the pitch, drawing the shortstop or second baseman over to second base, creating a gap in the infield for the batter to poke the ball through.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The sacrifice bunt, calls for the batter to focus on making soft contact with the ball, so that it rolls a short distance into the infield, allowing the runner to advance into scoring position as the batter is thrown out at first.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] A batter, particularly one who is a fast runner, may also attempt to bunt for a hit.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] A sacrifice bunt employed with a runner on third base, aimed at bringing that runner home, is known as a squeeze play.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] With a runner on third and fewer than two outs, a batter may instead concentrate on hitting a fly ball that, even if it is caught, will be deep enough to allow the runner to tag up and score—a successful batter, in this case, gets credit for a sacrifice fly.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In order to increase the chance of advancing a batter to first base via a walk, the manager will sometimes signal a batter who is ahead in the count (i.e., has more balls than strikes) to take, or not swing at, the next pitch.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The batter's potential reward of reaching base (via a walk) exceeds the disadvantage if the next pitch is a strike.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Consensus once held that today's baseball is a North American development from the older game rounders, popular among children in Great Britain and Ireland.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] American baseball historian David Block suggests that the game originated in England; recently uncovered historical evidence supports this position.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] According to Block and official MLB historian John Thorn, this earlier version of baseball may have involved hitting the ball with a hand, making it akin to today's punchball.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Block argues that rounders and early baseball were actually regional variants of each other, and that the game's most direct antecedents are the English games of stoolball and "tut-ball".
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The earliest known reference to baseball is in a 1744 British publication, *A Little Pretty Pocket-Book*, by John Newbery.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Block discovered that the first recorded game of "Base Ball" took place in 1749 in Surrey, and featured the Prince of Wales as a player.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] This early form of the game was apparently brought to Canada by English immigrants.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] By the early 1830s, there were reports of a variety of uncodified bat-and-ball games recognizable as early forms of baseball being played around North America.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The first recorded baseball game in North America was played in Beachville, Ontario, Canada, on June 4, 1838.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In 1845, Alexander Cartwright, a member of New York City's Knickerbocker Club, led the codification of the so-called Knickerbocker Rules, which in turn were based on rules developed in 1837 by William R.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] While there are reports that the New York Knickerbockers played games in 1845, the contest long recognized as the first recorded baseball game in U.S. history took place on June 19, 1846, in Hoboken, New Jersey: the "New York Nine" defeated the Knickerbockers, 23–1, in four innings.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] With the Knickerbocker code as the basis, the rules of modern baseball continued to evolve over the next half-century.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The game then went on to spread throughout the Pacific Rim and the Americas, with Americans backing the sport as a way to spread American values.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In the mid-1850s, a baseball craze hit the New York metropolitan area, and by 1856, local journals were referring to baseball as the "national pastime" or "national game".
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] A year later, the sport's first governing body, the National Association of Base Ball Players, was formed.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In 1867, it barred participation by African Americans.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The more formally structured National League was founded in 1876.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Professional Negro leagues formed, but quickly folded.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In 1887, softball, under the name of indoor baseball or indoor-outdoor, was invented as a winter version of the parent game.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The American League evolved from the minor Western League, which was reorganized under Ban Johnson in 1893.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] It was not until 1901 that the American League was formally established as a major league.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] By 1893, crucial structural changes (like moving the pitching distance to 60 feet, 6 inches) firmly cemented the modern rulebook.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The National Agreement of 1903 formalized relations both between the two major leagues and between them and the National Association of Professional Base Ball Leagues, representing most of the country's minor professional leagues.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The World Series, pitting the two major league champions against each other, was inaugurated that fall.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The Black Sox Scandal of the 1919 World Series led to the formation of the office of the Commissioner of Baseball.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The first commissioner, Kenesaw Mountain Landis, was elected in 1920.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] That year also saw the founding of the Negro National League; the first significant Negro league, it would operate until 1931.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] For part of the 1920s, it was joined by the Eastern Colored League.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Compared with the present, professional baseball in the early 20th century was lower-scoring, and pitchers were more dominant.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] This so-called "dead-ball era" ended in the early 1920s with several changes in rule and circumstance that were advantageous to hitters.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Strict new regulations that governed the ball's size, shape and composition, along with a new rule officially banning the spitball and other pitches that depended on the ball being treated or roughed-up with foreign substances, resulted in a ball that traveled farther when hit.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The rise of the legendary player Babe Ruth, the first great power hitter of the new era, helped permanently alter the nature of the game.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Louis Cardinals general manager Branch Rickey invested in several minor league clubs and developed the first modern farm system.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] A new Negro National League was organized in 1933; four years later, it was joined by the Negro American League.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The first elections to the National Baseball Hall of Fame took place in 1936.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In 1939, Little League Baseball was founded in Pennsylvania.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Many minor league teams disbanded when World War II led to a player shortage.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Wrigley led the formation of the All-American Girls Professional Baseball League to help keep the game in the public eye.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The first crack in the unwritten agreement barring blacks from white-controlled professional ball occurred in 1945: Jackie Robinson was signed by the National League's Brooklyn Dodgers and began playing for their minor league team in Montreal.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In 1947, Robinson broke the major leagues' color barrier when he debuted with the Dodgers.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Latin-American players, largely overlooked before, also started entering the majors in greater numbers.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In 1951, two Chicago White Sox, Venezuelan-born Chico Carrasquel and black Cuban-born Minnie Miñoso, became the first Hispanic All-Stars.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Integration proceeded slowly: by 1953, only six of the 16 major league teams had a black player on the roster.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In 1975, the union's power—and players' salaries—began to increase greatly when the reserve clause was effectively struck down, leading to the free agency system.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Significant work stoppages occurred in 1981 and 1994, the latter forcing the cancellation of the World Series for the first time in 90 years.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Attendance had been growing steadily since the mid-1970s and in 1994, before the stoppage, the majors were setting their all-time record for per-game attendance.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] After play resumed in 1995, non-division-winning wild card teams became a permanent fixture of the post-season.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Regular-season interleague play was introduced in 1997 and the second-highest attendance mark for a full season was set.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In 2000, the National and American Leagues were dissolved as legal entities.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] While their identities were maintained for scheduling purposes (and the designated hitter distinction), the regulations and other functions—such as player discipline and umpire supervision—they had administered separately were consolidated under the rubric of MLB.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In 2001, Barry Bonds established the current record of 73 home runs in a single season.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In 2007, Bonds became MLB's all-time home run leader, surpassing Hank Aaron, as total major league and minor league attendance both reached all-time highs.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Despite having been called "America's national pastime", baseball is well-established in several other countries.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] As early as 1877, a professional league, the International Association, featured teams from both Canada and the United States.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] While baseball is widely played in Canada and many minor league teams have been based in the country, the American major leagues did not include a Canadian club until 1969, when the Montreal Expos joined the National League as an expansion team.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In 1977, the expansion Toronto Blue Jays joined the American League.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In 1847, American soldiers played what may have been the first baseball game in Mexico at Parque Los Berros in Xalapa, Veracruz.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The first formal baseball league outside of the United States and Canada was founded in 1878 in Cuba, which maintains a rich baseball tradition.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The English football club, Aston Villa, were the first British baseball champions winning the 1890 National League of Baseball of Great Britain.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The 2025 National Champions were the London Mets.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The Dominican Republic held its first islandwide championship tournament in 1912.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Professional baseball tournaments and leagues began to form in other countries between the world wars, including the Netherlands (formed in 1922), Australia (1934), Japan (1936), Mexico (1937), and Puerto Rico (1938).
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The Japanese major leagues have long been considered the highest quality professional circuits outside of the United States.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] After World War II, professional leagues were founded in many Latin American countries, most prominently Venezuela (1946) and the Dominican Republic (1955).
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Since the early 1970s, the annual Caribbean Series has matched the championship clubs from the four leading Latin American winter leagues: the Dominican Professional Baseball League, Mexican Pacific League, Puerto Rican Professional Baseball League, and Venezuelan Professional Baseball League.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In Asia, South Korea (1982), Taiwan (1990) and China (2003) all have professional leagues.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Other European countries have seen professional leagues; the most successful, other than the Dutch league, is the Italian league, founded in 1948.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In 2004, Australia won a surprise silver medal at the Olympic Games.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The Confédération Européene de Baseball (European Baseball Confederation), founded in 1953, organizes a number of competitions between clubs from different countries.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Women's baseball is played on an organized amateur basis in numerous countries.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] After being admitted to the Olympics as a medal sport beginning with the 1992 Games, baseball was dropped from the 2012 Summer Olympic Games at the 2005 International Olympic Committee meeting.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] While the sport's lack of a following in much of the world was a factor, more important was MLB's reluctance to allow its players to participate during the major league season.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] MLB initiated the World Baseball Classic, scheduled to precede its season, partly as a replacement, high-profile international tournament.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The inaugural Classic, held in March 2006, was the first tournament involving national teams to feature a significant number of MLB participants.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The Baseball World Cup was discontinued after its 2011 edition in favor of an expanded World Baseball Classic.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Baseball has certain attributes that set it apart from the other popular team sports in the countries where it has a following.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] All of these sports use a clock, play is less individual, and the variation between playing fields is not as substantial or important.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The comparison between cricket and baseball demonstrates that many of baseball's distinctive elements are shared in various ways with similar sports.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In clock-limited sports, games often end with a team that holds the lead killing the clock rather than competing aggressively against the opposing team.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In contrast, baseball has no clock, thus a team cannot win without getting the last batter out and rallies are not constrained by time.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] At almost any turn in any baseball game, the most advantageous strategy is some form of aggressive strategy.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] While nine innings has been the standard since the beginning of professional baseball, the duration of the average major league game has increased steadily through the years.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] At the turn of the 20th century, games typically took an hour and a half to play.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In the 1920s, they averaged just less than two hours, which eventually ballooned to 2:38 in 1960.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] By 1997, the average American League game lasted 2:57 (National League games were about 10 minutes shorter—pitchers at the plate making for quicker outs than designated hitters).
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In 2004, Major League Baseball declared that its goal was an average game of 2:45.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] By 2014, though, the average MLB game took over three hours to complete.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The lengthening of games is attributed to longer breaks between half-innings for television commercials, increased offense, more pitching changes, and a slower pace of play, with pitchers taking more time between each delivery, and batters stepping out of the box more frequently.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Other leagues have experienced similar issues.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In 2008, Nippon Professional Baseball took steps aimed at shortening games by 12 minutes from the preceding decade's average of 3:18.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In 2016, the average nine-inning playoff game in Major League baseball was 3 hours and 35 minutes.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] This was up 10 minutes from 2015 and 21 minutes from 2014.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In response to the lengthening of the game, MLB decided from the 2023 season onward to institute a pitch clock rule to penalize batters and pitchers who take too much time between pitches; this had the effect of shortening 2023 regular season games by 24 minutes on average.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Although baseball is a team sport, individual players are often placed under scrutiny and pressure.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] While rewarding, it has sometimes been described as "ruthless" due to the pressure on the individual player.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] In 1915, a baseball instructional manual pointed out that every single pitch, of which there are often more than two hundred in a game, involves an individual, one-on-one contest: "the pitcher and the batter in a battle of wits".
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Pitcher, batter, and fielder all act essentially independent of each other.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] While coaching staffs can signal pitcher or batter to pursue certain tactics, the execution of the play itself is a series of solitary acts.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] If the batter hits a line drive, the outfielder is solely responsible for deciding to try to catch it or play it on the bounce and for succeeding or failing.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The statistical precision of baseball is both facilitated by this isolation and reinforces it.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] There is no statistical equivalent in cricket for the fielding error and thus less emphasis on personal responsibility in this area of play.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Unlike those of most sports, baseball playing fields can vary significantly in size and shape.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Major league teams often skirt even this rule.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] For example, at Daikin Park, which became the home of the Houston Astros in 2000, the Crawford Boxes in left field are only 315 feet (96 m) from home plate.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] There are no rules at all that address the height of fences or other structures at the edge of the outfield.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The most famously idiosyncratic outfield boundary is the left-field wall at Boston's Fenway Park, in use since 1912: the Green Monster is 310 feet (94 m) from home plate down the line and 37 feet (11 m) tall.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Similarly, there are no regulations at all concerning the dimensions of foul territory.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Thus a foul fly ball may be entirely out of play in a park with little space between the foul lines and the stands, but a foulout in a park with more expansive foul ground.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] A fence in foul territory that is close to the outfield line will tend to direct balls that strike it back toward the fielders, while one that is farther away may actually prompt more collisions, as outfielders run full speed to field balls deep in the corner.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] These variations can make the difference between a double and a triple or inside-the-park home run.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The surface of the field is also unregulated.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] While the adjacent image shows a traditional field surfacing arrangement (and the one used by virtually all MLB teams with naturally surfaced fields), teams are free to decide what areas will be grassed or bare.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Some fields—including several in MLB—use artificial turf.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Surface variations can have a significant effect on how ground balls behave and are fielded as well as on baserunning.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Similarly, the presence of a roof (seven major league teams play in stadiums with permanent or retractable roofs) can greatly affect how fly balls are played.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] While football and soccer players deal with similar variations of field surface and stadium covering, the size and shape of their fields are much more standardized.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The area out-of-bounds on a football or soccer field does not affect play the way foul territory in baseball does, so variations in that regard are largely insignificant.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] These physical variations create a distinctive set of playing conditions at each ballpark.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Other local factors, such as altitude and climate, can also significantly affect play.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] A given stadium may acquire a reputation as a pitcher's park or a hitter's park, if one or the other discipline notably benefits from its unique mix of elements.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The most exceptional park in this regard is Coors Field, home of the Colorado Rockies.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Its high altitude—5,282 feet (1,610 m) above sea level—is partly responsible for giving it the strongest hitter's park effect in the major leagues due to the low air pressure.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] Wrigley Field, home of the Chicago Cubs, is known for its fickle disposition: a pitcher's park when the strong winds off Lake Michigan are blowing in, it becomes more of a hitter's park when they are blowing out.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] The absence of a standardized field affects not only how particular games play out, but the nature of team rosters and players' statistical records.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] For example, hitting a fly ball 330 feet (100 m) into right field might result in an easy catch on the warning track at one park, and a home run at another.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] A team that plays in a park with a relatively short right field, such as the New York Yankees, will tend to stock its roster with left-handed pull hitters, who can best exploit it.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p01] On the individual level, a player who spends most of his career with a team that plays in a hitter's park will gain an advantage in batting statistics over time—even more so if his talents are especially suited to the park.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Organized baseball lends itself to statistics to a greater degree than many other sports.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Each play is discrete and has a relatively small number of possible outcomes.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] The Official Baseball Rules administered by MLB require the official scorer to categorize each baseball play unambiguously.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] The rules provide detailed criteria to promote consistency.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] The score report is the official basis for both the box score of the game and the relevant statistical records.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] General managers, managers, and baseball scouts use statistics to evaluate players and make strategic decisions.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Certain traditional statistics are familiar to most baseball fans.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Among the many other statistics that are kept are those collectively known as *situational statistics*.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] For example, statistics can indicate which specific pitchers a certain batter performs best against.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] If a given situation statistically favors a certain batter, the manager of the fielding team may be more likely to change pitchers or have the pitcher intentionally walk the batter in order to face one who is less likely to succeed.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Sabermetrics is the field of baseball statistical study and the development of new statistics and analytical tools.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Such new statistics are also called sabermetrics.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] The term was coined around 1980 by one of the field's leading proponents, Bill James, and derives from the Society for American Baseball Research (SABR).
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Writing in 1919, philosopher Morris Raphael Cohen described baseball as the national religion of the US.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] In the words of sports columnist Jayson Stark, baseball has long been "a unique paragon of American culture"—a status he sees as devastated by the steroid abuse scandal.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] American influence in the Western Hemisphere has meant that baseball grew significantly in the region.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] A century later, the situation was very different.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] With the rise in popularity of other team sports with much higher average ticket prices—football, basketball, and hockey—professional baseball had become among the most popular blue-collar-oriented American spectator sports.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Overall, baseball has a large following in the United States; a 2006 poll found that nearly half of Americans are fans.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] This led to baseball being granted the title of "America's favorite pastime" by many American baseball fans.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] As historians and scholars now speculate, baseball is a metaphor of the American way of life In the late 1900s and early 2000s, baseball's position compared to football in the United States moved in contradictory directions.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] In 2008, MLB set a revenue record of $6.5 billion, matching the NFL's revenue for the first time in decades.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] A new MLB revenue record of more than $10 billion was set in 2017.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] On the other hand, the percentage of American sports fans polled who named baseball as their favorite sport was 9%, compared to pro football at 37%.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] In 1985, the respective figures were pro football 24%, baseball 23%.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Because there are so many more major league games played, there is no comparison in overall attendance.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] In 2008, total attendance at major league games was the second-highest in history: 78.6 million, 0.7% off the record set the previous year.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] The following year, amid the U.S. recession, attendance fell by 6.6% to 73.4 million.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Eight years later, it dropped under 73 million.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Attendance at games held under the Minor League Baseball umbrella set a record in 2008, with 43.3 million.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] While MLB games have not drawn the same national TV viewership as football games, MLB games are dominant in teams' local markets and regularly lead all programs in primetime in their markets during the summer.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] After multiple years of declines since 2017, baseball attendance has grown slightly in recent years.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] In 2024, attendance was 71.3 million, the highest since 2017.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Baseball is very popular in Venezuela; in 2011, 95% of people surveyed claimed it to be the national sport.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] In Nicaragua and Panama, baseball is also considered the national sport.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] While soccer is still more popular, baseball is a fast-growing sport in Mexico.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] In 2024, top Mexican League baseball teams outdraw some Liga MX teams in attendance.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Baseball also is somewhat popular in Colombia, though secondary to soccer, especially in coastal areas such as Barranquilla and Cartagena which are near the Caribbean.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] In recent years, baseball has grown in popularity in Colombia, especially in the capital of Bogotá, due an increase of Venezuelan immigrants.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] In Brazil, baseball fan popularity has grown in the last few years, thanks to MLB broadcasts in Brazilian ESPN and the historic silver medal in 2023 Pan-American games.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] However, it still lags behind basketball and American football in the list of most played sports in Brazil.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Baseball has also grown in popularity in Argentina and Peru in recent years due to Venezuelan immigrants.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Costa Rica has also seen a growth in the popularity of baseball.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Since 1987, baseballs have exclusively been made in the Costa Rican town of Turrialba.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] In recent years, Major leaguer Mauricio Dubón has made efforts to increase support for the sport in the country.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] The sport's overall popularity in Latin America has assisted in integrating Latin American migrants to the United States.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Since the early 1980s, the Dominican Republic, in particular the city of San Pedro de Macorís, has been the major leagues' primary source of foreign talent.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] In 2017, 83 of the 868 players on MLB Opening Day rosters (and disabled lists) were from the country.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Among other Caribbean countries and territories, a combined 97 MLB players were born in Venezuela, Cuba, and Puerto Rico.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Hall-of-Famer Roberto Clemente remains one of the greatest national heroes in Puerto Rico's history.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] While baseball has long been the island's primary athletic pastime, its once well-attended professional winter league has declined in popularity since 1990, when young Puerto Rican players began to be included in the major leagues' annual first-year player draft.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] In Cuba, where baseball is by every reckoning the national sport, the national team overshadows the city and provincial teams that play in the top-level domestic leagues.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Baseball is also one of the most popular sports of Aruba and Curaçao, and a growing sport in The Bahamas and the US Virgin Islands.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] In East Asia, baseball is among the most popular sports in Japan, Taiwan and South Korea.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] In Japan, where baseball is inarguably the leading spectator team sport, combined revenue for the twelve teams in Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB), the body that oversees both the Central and Pacific Leagues, was estimated at $1 billion in 2007.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Total NPB attendance for the year was approximately 20 million.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] While in the preceding two decades, MLB attendance grew by 50 percent and revenue nearly tripled, the comparable NPB figures were stagnant.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] There are concerns that MLB's growing interest in acquiring star Japanese players will hurt the game in their home country.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Revenue figures are not released for the country's amateur system.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Similarly, according to one official pronouncement, the sport's governing authority "has never taken into account attendance ... because its greatest interest has always been the development of athletes".
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] In Taiwan, baseball is one of the most widely spectated sports, in TV and person.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Baseball has grown significantly in China in recent years, with MLB estimating in 2019 that there are 21 million active fans in the country.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Baseball was considered a national pastime in the Philippines in the 1960s and 70s, but the sport has since declined in popularity.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Since 2005, there have been efforts to revitalize the sport in the country.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Baseball saw a surge in popularity in Thailand following the countries' silver medal in baseball in the 2025 SEA Games, which were hosted in Thailand.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Baseball is generally a niche sport in Europe.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] However, baseball is somewhat popular in the Netherlands, where it is known as *honkbal*, thanks to influence from the United States after World War II and the Kingdoms control over Aruba and Curaçao where it is the most popular sport.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Baseball is also somewhat popular in portions of Italy, especially in the town of Nettuno, due to influence from American soldiers after World War II.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Baseball has grown in recent years in the Czech Republic, due in part to the Czech teams' success in the 2023 World Baseball Classic.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Baseball is one of the most popular sports in Palau and Guam.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] In Australia, baseball is a niche sport but the country does have a professional league.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Because the league is played in winter for the western hemisphere, it attracts American and Korean professional players looking to play winter league baseball.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] In 2026, there were more than 30 Australians playing college baseball in the United States compared to six in 2020.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] The Dodgers operate a large baseball academy in Mpigi, Uganda, and there are also baseball programs in Luwero, Uganda.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] There is also a Africa Baseball Academy in Nairobi, Nigeria.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Baseball was popular in South Africa prior to World War 2 but popularity has since waned.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] There are still teams and attempts to raise the popularity of baseball in the country, including the introduction of Baseball5.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] There is a growing baseball program in South Sudan, which has resulted in professional contracts.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] The Japan-Africa Baseball & Softball Foundation has created Koshien high school baseball tournaments in Tanzania, Ghana and Kenya, which Tanzania being the most successful.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] There are further plans for similar tournaments in Nigeria, South Sudan, Benin, Cameroon and Zambia.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] As of 2024, Little League Baseball oversees leagues with 2 million participants in more than 80 countries.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] The number of players has fallen since the 1990s, when 3 million children took part in Little League Baseball annually.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Babe Ruth League teams have over 1 million participants.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] According to the president of the International Baseball Federation in 2009, between 300,000 and 500,000 women and girls play baseball around the world, including Little League and the introductory game of Tee Ball.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] A varsity baseball team is an established part of physical education departments at most high schools and colleges in the United States.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] In 2015, nearly half a million high schoolers and over 34,000 collegians played on their schools' baseball teams.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] By early in the 20th century, intercollegiate baseball was Japan's leading sport.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Today, high school baseball in particular is immensely popular there.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] The final rounds of the two annual tournaments—the National High School Baseball Invitational Tournament in the spring, and the even more important National High School Baseball Championship in the summer—are broadcast around the country.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] The tournaments are known, respectively, as Spring Koshien and Summer Koshien after the 55,000-capacity stadium where they are played.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] In Cuba, baseball is a mandatory part of the state system of physical education, which begins at age six.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Talented children as young as seven are sent to special district schools for more intensive training—the first step on a ladder whose acme is the national baseball team.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Baseball has had a broad impact on popular culture, both in the United States and elsewhere.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Dozens of English-language idioms have been derived from baseball; in particular, the game is the source of a number of widely used sexual euphemisms.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] The first networked radio broadcasts in North America were of the 1922 World Series: famed sportswriter Grantland Rice announced play-by-play from New York City's Polo Grounds on WJZ–Newark, New Jersey, which was connected by wire to WGY–Schenectady, New York, and WBZ–Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] The baseball cap has become a ubiquitous fashion item not only in the United States and Japan, but also in countries where the sport itself is not particularly popular, such as the United Kingdom.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Baseball has inspired many works of art and entertainment.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] There have been many baseball movies, including the Academy Award–winning *The Pride of the Yankees* (1942) and the Oscar nominees *The Natural* (1984) and *Field of Dreams* (1989).
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] The American Film Institute's selection of the ten best sports movies includes *The Pride of the Yankees* at number 3 and *Bull Durham* (1988) at number 5.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Baseball has provided thematic material for hits on both stage—the Adler–Ross musical *Damn Yankees*—and record—George J.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Gaskin's "Slide, Kelly, Slide", Simon and Garfunkel's "Mrs.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Robinson", and John Fogerty's "Centerfield".
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] The baseball-inspired comedic sketch "Who's on First?", popularized by Abbott and Costello in 1938, quickly became famous; six decades later, *Time* named it the best comedy routine of the 20th century.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Literary works connected to the game include the short fiction of Ring Lardner and novels such as Bernard Malamud's *The Natural* (the source for the movie), Robert Coover's *The Universal Baseball Association, Inc., J.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Henry Waugh, Prop.*, John Grisham's Calico Joe and W.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Kinsella's *Shoeless Joe* (the source for *Field of Dreams*).
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Baseball's literary canon also includes the beat reportage of Damon Runyon; the columns of Grantland Rice, Red Smith, Dick Young, and Peter Gammons; and the essays of Roger Angell.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Among the celebrated nonfiction books in the field are Lawrence S.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Ritter's *The Glory of Their Times*, Roger Kahn's *The Boys of Summer*, and Michael Lewis's *Moneyball*.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] The 1970 publication of major league pitcher Jim Bouton's tell-all chronicle *Ball Four* is considered a turning point in the reporting of professional sports.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Baseball has also inspired the creation of new cultural forms.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Baseball cards were introduced in the late 19th century as trade cards.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] A typical example featured an image of a baseball player on one side and advertising for a business on the other.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] In the early 1900s they were produced widely as promotional items by tobacco and confectionery companies.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] The 1930s saw the popularization of the modern style of baseball card, with a player photograph accompanied on the rear by statistics and biographical data.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Baseball cards—many of which are now prized collectibles—are the source of the much broader trading card industry, involving similar products for different sports and non-sports-related fields.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Modern fantasy sports began in 1980 with the invention of Rotisserie League Baseball by New York writer Daniel Okrent and several friends.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Participants in a Rotisserie league draft notional teams from the list of active MLB players and play out an entire imaginary season with game outcomes based on the players' latest real-world statistics.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Rotisserie-style play quickly became a phenomenon.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Now known more generically as fantasy baseball, it has inspired similar games based on an array of different sports.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] The field boomed with increasing Internet access and new fantasy sports-related websites.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] By 2008, 29.9 million people in the United States and Canada were playing fantasy sports, spending $800 million on the hobby.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] The burgeoning popularity of fantasy baseball is also credited with the increasing attention paid to sabermetrics—first among fans, only later among baseball professionals.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Informal variations of baseball have popped up over time, with games like corkball reflecting local traditions and allowing the game to be played in diverse environments.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Two variations of baseball, softball and Baseball5, are internationally governed alongside baseball by the World Baseball Softball Confederation.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] American professional baseball teams toured Britain in 1874 and 1889, and had a great effect on similar sports in Britain.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] In Wales and Merseyside, a strong community game had already developed with skills and plays more in keeping with the American game and the Welsh began to informally adopt the name "baseball" (Pêl Fas), to reflect the American style.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] By the 1890s, calls were made to follow the success of other working class sports (like Rugby in Wales and Soccer in Merseyside) and adopt a distinct set of rules and bureaucracy.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] During the 1892 season rules for the game of "baseball" were agreed and the game was officially codified.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] Finnish baseball, also known as pesäpallo, is a combination of traditional ball-batting team games and North American baseball, invented by Lauri "Tahko" Pihkala in the 1920s.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] The basic idea of pesäpallo is similar to that of baseball: the offense tries to score by hitting the ball successfully and running through the bases, while the defense tries to put the batter and runners out.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] One of the most important differences between pesäpallo and baseball is that the ball is pitched vertically, which makes hitting the ball, as well as controlling the power and direction of the hit, much easier.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-p02] This gives the offensive game more variety, speed, and tactical aspects compared to baseball.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] In baseball, the **pitcher** is the player who throws ("pitches") the baseball from the pitcher's mound toward the catcher to begin each play, with the goal of retiring a batter, who attempts to either make contact with the pitched ball or draw a walk.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] In the defensive numbering system used in baseball, the pitcher is assigned the number 1.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] The pitcher is often considered the most important player on the defensive side of the game, and as such is situated at the right end of the defensive spectrum.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] There are many different types of pitchers, such as the starting pitcher, relief pitcher, middle reliever, lefty specialist, setup man, and the closer.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Starting in 1973 with the American League and spreading to further leagues throughout the 1980s and 1990s, the hitting duties of the pitcher have generally been given over to the position of designated hitter, a cause of some controversy.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] The National League adopted the designated hitter in 2022; as of 2026, the Japanese Central League is the highest level of competition to not use the designated hitter position.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] In most cases, the objective of the pitcher is to deliver the pitch to the catcher without allowing the batter to hit the ball with the bat.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] A successful pitch is delivered in such a way that the batter either allows the pitch to pass through the strike zone, swings the bat at the ball and misses it, or hits the ball poorly (resulting in a pop fly or ground out).
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] If the batter elects not to swing at the pitch, it is called a *strike* if any part of the ball passes through the strike zone and a *ball* when no part of the ball passes through the strike zone.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] A check swing is when the batter begins to swing, but then stops the swing short.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] If the batter successfully checks the swing and the pitch is out of the strike zone, it is called a ball.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] There are two legal pitching positions, the *windup* and the set position or *stretch*.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Either position may be used at any time; typically, the windup is used when the bases are empty, while the set position is used when at least one runner is on base.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Each position has certain procedures that must be followed.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] A balk can be called on a pitcher from either position.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] A power pitcher is one who relies on the velocity of his pitches to succeed.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Generally, power pitchers record a high percentage of strikeouts.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] A control pitcher succeeds by throwing accurate pitches and thus records few walks.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Nearly all action during a game is centered on the pitcher for the defensive team.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] A pitcher's particular style, time taken between pitches, and skill heavily influence the dynamics of the game and can often determine the victor.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Starting with the pivot foot on the *pitcher's rubber* at the center of the pitcher's mound, which is 60 feet 6 inches (18.44 m) from *home plate*, the pitcher throws the baseball to the catcher, who is positioned behind home plate and catches the ball.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Meanwhile, a batter stands in the batter's box at one side of the plate, and attempts to bat the ball safely into fair play.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] The type and sequence of pitches chosen depend upon the particular situation in a game.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Because pitchers and catchers must coordinate each pitch, a system of hand signals is used by the catcher to communicate choices to the pitcher, who either vetoes or accepts by shaking his head or nodding.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] The relationship between pitcher and catcher is so important that some teams select the starting catcher for a particular game based on the starting pitcher.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Together, the pitcher and catcher are known as the *battery*.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Although the object and mechanics of pitching remain the same, pitchers may be classified according to their roles and effectiveness.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] The starting pitcher begins the game, and he may be followed by various relief pitchers, such as the long reliever, the left-handed specialist, the middle reliever, the setup man, and/or the closer.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] In abbreviating baseball positions, **P** is used as a general designation for pitchers.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] **SP** and **RP** are sometimes used to differentiate starting and relief pitchers, respectively, while **LHP** and **RHP** are sometimes used to indicate if a pitcher is left-handed or right-handed, respectively.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] In Major League Baseball, baseball rubbing mud is used to condition game balls before pitchers use them.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] A skilled pitcher often throws various pitches to prevent the batter from hitting the ball well.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] The most basic pitch is a fastball, where the pitcher throws the ball as hard as possible.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Some pitchers are able to throw a fastball at a speed over 105 miles per hour (169 km/h; 154 ft/s), such as Aroldis Chapman, Ben Joyce, and Jacob Misiorowski.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Other common types of pitches are the curveball, slider, changeup, cutter, sinker, screwball, forkball, split-fingered fastball, slurve, knuckleball, and vulcan.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] These generally are intended to have unusual movement or to deceive the batter as to the rotation or velocity of the ball, making it more difficult to hit.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Few pitchers throw all these pitches, but most use a subset or blend of the basic types.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Some pitchers release pitches from different arm angles, making it harder for the batter to pick up the ball's flight.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Pitchers use several distinct throwing styles.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] The most common style is a three-quarters delivery in which the pitcher's arm snaps downward with the ball's release.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Some pitchers use a sidearm delivery in which the arm arcs laterally to the torso.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Some pitchers use a submarine style in which the pitcher's body tilts sharply downward on delivery, creating an exaggerated sidearm motion in which the pitcher's knuckles come very close to the mound.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Effective pitching is vitally important in baseball.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] In baseball statistics, for each game, one pitcher will be credited with winning the game, and one pitcher will be charged with losing it.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] These are not necessarily the starting pitchers for each team; however, a reliever can win, and the starter would then get a no-decision.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Pitching places significant physical demands on the body, with physiological responses during a game showing heart rate, oxygen consumption, and muscle enzyme changes indicative of moderate to high exercise intensity and potential muscle stress.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] A full game usually involves 120–170 pitches thrown by each team, and most pitchers begin to tire before they reach this point.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] As a result, the pitcher who starts a game often will not be the one who finishes it, and he may not be recovered enough to pitch again for a few days.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] The act of throwing a baseball at high speed is very unnatural to the body and somewhat damaging to human muscles; thus pitchers are very susceptible to injuries, soreness, and general pain.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Baseball teams use two strategies to address this problem: rotation and specialization.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] To accommodate playing nearly every day, a team will include a group of pitchers who start games and rotate between them, allowing each pitcher to rest for a few days between starts.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] A team's roster of starting pitchers are usually not even in terms of skill.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Exceptional pitchers are highly sought after and in the professional ranks draw large salaries, thus teams can seldom stock each slot in the rotation with top-quality pitchers.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] The best starter in the team's rotation is called the ace.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] He is usually followed in the rotation by 3 or 4 other starters before he would be due to pitch again.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Barring injury or exceptional circumstances, the ace is usually the pitcher that starts on Opening Day.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Aces are also preferred to start crucial games late in the season and in the playoffs; sometimes they are asked to pitch on shorter rest if the team feels he would be more effective than the 4th or 5th starter.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Typically, the further down in the rotation a starting pitcher is, the weaker he is compared with the others on the staff.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] The "5th starter" is seen as the cut-off between the starting staff and the *bullpen*.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] A team may have a designated 5th starter, sometimes known as a spot starter or that role may shift cycle to cycle between members of the bullpen or Triple-A starters.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Differences in rotation setup could also have tactical considerations as well, such as alternating right- or left-handed pitchers, in order to throw off the other team's hitting game-to-game in a series.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Teams have additional pitchers reserved to replace that game's starting pitcher if he tires or proves ineffective.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] These players are called *relief pitchers*, *relievers*, or collectively the *bullpen*.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Once a starter begins to tire or is starting to give up hits and runs a call is made to the bullpen to have a reliever start to warm up.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] This involves the reliever starting to throw practice balls to a coach in the bullpen so as to be ready to come in and pitch whenever the manager wishes to pull the current pitcher.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Having a reliever warm up does not always mean he will be used; the current pitcher may regain his composure and retire the side, or the manager may choose to go with another reliever if strategy dictates.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Commonly, pitching changes will occur as a result of a pinch hitter being used in the late innings of a game, especially if the pitcher is in the batting lineup due to not having the designated hitter.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] A reliever would then come out of the bullpen to pitch the next inning.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] When making a pitching change a manager will come out to the mound.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] He will then call in a pitcher by the tap of the arm which the next pitcher throws with.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] The manager or pitching coach may also come out to discuss strategy with the pitcher, but on his second trip to the mound with the same pitcher in the same inning, the pitcher has to come out.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] It is considered proper etiquette for the pitcher to wait on the mound until the manager arrives, whereby he then hands the manager the ball, and only then he is allowed to leave the field.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Relief pitchers often have even more specialized roles, and the particular reliever used depends on the situation.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Many teams designate one pitcher as the *closer*, a relief pitcher specifically reserved to pitch the final inning or innings of a game when his team has a narrow lead, in order to preserve the victory.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] More recently, teams began experimenting with an *opener*, a relief pitcher who starts a game but only pitches at least the first inning.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Other relief roles include set-up men, middle relievers, left-handed specialists, and long relievers.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Generally, relievers pitch fewer innings and throw fewer pitches than starters, but they can usually pitch more frequently without the need for several days of rest between appearances.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Relief pitchers are typically pitchers with "special stuff", meaning that they have very effective pitches or a very different style of delivery.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] This makes the batter see a very different way of pitching in attempt to get them out.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] One example is a sidearm or submarine pitcher.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Position players are eligible to pitch in a game as well, this however is rare as these players are not truly trained as pitchers and risk injury.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] (For instance, in a 1993 game, Jose Canseco suffered a season ending arm injury after pitching 2 innings.) Plus, they tend to throw with less velocity and skill.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] For these reasons, managers will typically only use a position player as a pitcher in a blowout loss, or if they have run out of available pitchers in order to avoid a forfeit (the latter typically only happens in extra-inning games).
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] The only regulation game in which *both* pitchers of record were position players occurred on May 6, 2012, when the Baltimore Orioles' designated hitter Chris Davis was the winner in a 16-inning game against Boston while Red Sox outfielder Darnell McDonald took the loss.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] The pitcher's duty does not cease after he pitches the ball.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Unlike the other fielders, a pitcher and catcher must start every play in a designated area.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] The pitcher must be on the pitcher's mound, with one foot in contact with the pitcher's rubber, and the catcher must be behind home plate in the catcher's box.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Once the ball is in play, however, the pitcher and catcher, like the other fielders, can respond to any part of the field necessary to make or assist in a defensive play.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] At that point, the pitcher has several standard roles.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] The pitcher must attempt to field any balls coming up the middle, and in fact a Gold Glove Award is reserved for the pitcher with the best fielding ability.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] He must head over to first base, to be available to cover it, on balls hit to the right side, since the first baseman might be fielding them too far to the baseman's right to reach first base before the batter-runner can.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Except for the first baseman, the pitcher ordinarily has the shortest run to first base of anyone, and is the second-most-likely person to make a putout at first base by retrieving a fielded ball thrown by an infielder (typically a first baseman).
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] On passed balls and wild pitches, he covers home-plate when there are runners on.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Also, he generally backs up throws to home plate.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] When there is a throw from the outfield to third base, he has to back up the play to third base as well.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] The physical act of overhand pitching is complex and unnatural to the human anatomy.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Most major league pitchers throw at speeds of 70 to 100 mph (110 to 160 km/h), putting high amounts of stress on the pitching arm.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Pitchers are by far the most frequently injured players and many professional pitchers will have multiple surgeries to repair damage in the elbow and shoulder by the end of their careers.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] As such, the biomechanics of pitching are closely studied and taught by coaches at all levels and are an important field in sports medicine.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] The overhead throwing motion can be divided into phases which include windup, early cocking, late cocking, early acceleration, late acceleration, deceleration, and follow-through.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Training for pitchers often includes targeting one or several of these phases.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Biomechanical evaluations are sometimes done on individual pitchers to help determine points of inefficiency.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Some players begin intense mechanical training at a young age, a practice that has been criticized by many coaches and doctors, with some citing an increase in Tommy John surgeries in recent years.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Fleisig lists nine recommendations for preventative care of children's arms.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] 1) Watch and respond to signs of fatigue.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] 2) Youth pitchers should not pitch competitively in more than 8 months in any 12-month period.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] 3) Follow limits for pitch counts and days of rest.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] 4) Youth pitchers should avoid pitching on multiple teams with overlapping seasons.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] 5) Youth pitchers should learn good throwing mechanics as soon as possible: basic throwing, fastball pitching and change-up pitching.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] 7) A pitcher should not also be a catcher for their team.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] The pitcher catcher combination results in many throws and may increase the risk of injury.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] 8) If a pitcher complains of pain in their elbow, get an evaluation from a sports medicine physician.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] 9) Inspire youth to have fun playing baseball and other sports.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Participation and enjoyment of various activities will increase the youth's athleticism and interest in sports.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] To counteract shoulder and elbow injury, coaches and trainers have begun utilizing "jobe" exercises, named for Frank Jobe, the pioneer of the Tommy John procedure.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Jobes are exercises that have been developed to isolate, strengthen and stabilize the rotator cuff muscles.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Jobes can be done using either resistance bands or lightweight dumbbells.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Common jobe exercises include shoulder external rotation, shoulder flexion, horizontal abduction, prone abduction and scaption (at 45°, 90° and inverse 45°).
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] In addition to the Jobes exercises, many pitching coaches are creating lifting routines that are specialized for pitchers.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Pitchers should avoid exercises that deal with a barbell.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] The emphasis on the workout should be on the legs and the core.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Other body parts should be worked on but using lighter weights.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Over lifting muscles, especially while throwing usually ends up in a strain muscle or possibly a tear.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Other than the catcher, pitchers and other fielders wear very few pieces of equipment.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] In general the ball cap, baseball glove and cleats are equipment used.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Pitchers may also keep with them at the mound a bag of powdered rosin.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Handling the bag applies a small layer of the rosin to the pitcher's fingers in order to increase his grip on the ball.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] Currently there is a new trend of introducing a pitcher helmet to provide head protection from batters hitting line drives back to the pitcher.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] As of January 2014, MLB approved a protective pitchers cap which can be worn by any pitcher if they choose.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] San Diego Padres relief pitcher, Alex Torres was the first player in MLB to wear the protective cap.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] One style of helmet is worn on top of the ballcap to provide protection to the forehead and sides.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] In softball, a full face helmet is available to all players including pitchers.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-pitcher] These fielder's masks are becoming increasingly popular in younger fast pitch leagues, some leagues even requiring them.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-positions] In the sport of baseball, each of the nine players on a team is assigned a particular **fielding position** when it is their turn to play defense.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-positions] Each position conventionally has an associated number, for use in scorekeeping by the official scorer: 1 (pitcher), 2 (catcher), 3 (first baseman), 4 (second baseman), 5 (third baseman), 6 (shortstop), 7 (left fielder), 8 (center fielder), and 9 (right fielder).
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-positions] Collectively, these positions are usually grouped into three groups: the outfield (left field, center field, and right field), the infield (first base, second base, third base, and shortstop), and the battery (pitcher and catcher).
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-positions] Fielders must be able to catch the ball well, as catching batted balls before they bounce is one way they can put the batter out, as well as create opportunities to prevent the advance of, and put out other runners.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-positions] Fielders often have to run, dive, and slide a great deal in the act of reaching, stopping, and retrieving a hit ball, and then setting themselves up to transfer the ball, all with the end goal of getting the ball as quickly as possible to another fielder.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-positions] They also run the risk of colliding with incoming runners during a tag attempt at a base.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-positions] Fielders may have different responsibilities depending on the game situation.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-positions] For example, when an outfielder is attempting to throw the ball from near the fence to one of the bases, an infielder may need to "cut off" the throw and then act as a relay thrower to help the ball cover its remaining distance to the target destination.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-positions] As a group, the outfielders are responsible for preventing home runs by reaching over the fence (and potentially doing a wall climb) for fly balls that are catchable.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-positions] The infielders are the ones who generally handle plays that involve tagging a base or runner, and also need quick reflexes in order to catch a batted ball before it leaves the infield.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-positions] The pitcher and catcher have special responsibilities to prevent base stealing, as they are the ones who handle the ball whenever it has not been hit.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/baseball-positions] The catcher will also sometimes attempt to block the plate in order to prevent a run being scored.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/fly-ball-pitcher] A **fly ball pitcher** is a type of baseball pitcher who produces an above-average number of fly balls, typically by keeping his fastball high up in the strike zone and relying on late movement to cause the batter to be unable to make solid contact.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/fly-ball-pitcher] This designation is constructed around the ground ball fly ball ratio, which measures how frequently a pitcher gets batters out on fly balls versus ground balls.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/fly-ball-pitcher] The downside of a fly ball pitcher is that, in a ballpark where the design tends to favor hitters over pitchers (an example being Yankee Stadium), a fly ball pitcher will tend to give up more home runs, resulting in a higher earned run average.
[src:fly-ball-pitcher/fly-ball-pitcher] Examples include pitchers Sid Fernandez, Ted Lilly, Chris Young, Marco Estrada, Shota Imanaga and Dylan Cease.
